      "slug": "a-letter-to-worship-leaders",
      "title": "A Letter to Worship Leaders: Watch Out for \"Words in Sheep's Clothing",
      "type": "resource",
      "tags": [
        "worship",
        "lyrics",
        "therapeutic-language",
        "sin",
        "church"
      ],
      "created": "2026-04-11",
      "updated": "2026-04-11",
      "sources": "1",
      "domain": "faith",
      "excerpt": "Author: titus-jr-laxa\nPublished: 2024-08-12\nSource: https://tituslaxajr.substack.com/p/a-letter-to-worship-leaders-watch --- A critique of Contemporary Christian Music (CCM) for emphasizing therapeutic language...",
      "htmlContent": "<h1 id=\"a-letter-to-worship-leaders-watch-out-for-quot-words-in-sheep-39-s-clothing-quot\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">A Letter to Worship Leaders: Watch Out for &quot;Words in Sheep&#39;s Clothing&quot;</h1>\n<p class=\"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-on-surface-variant\"><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Author:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">entry.html?slug=titus-jr-laxa</a>\n<strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Published:</strong> 2024-08-12\n<strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Source:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">https://tituslaxajr.substack.com/p/a-letter-to-worship-leaders-watch</a></p>\n<hr class=\"my-12 border-0 border-t border-outline-variant/20\">\n<h1 id=\"summary\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">Summary</h1>\n<p class=\"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-on-surface-variant\">A critique of Contemporary Christian Music (CCM) for emphasizing therapeutic language (&quot;broken,&quot; &quot;messed up&quot;) over biblical language (&quot;sin,&quot; &quot;sinner&quot;). The article argues that words repeated in worship songs become teaching, and when sin-language is muted while brokenness-language is amplified, congregants learn to see themselves as victims rather than culpable sinners.</p>\n<hr class=\"my-12 border-0 border-t border-outline-variant/20\">\n<h1 id=\"key-points\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">Key Points</h1>\n<h1 id=\"quot-words-in-sheep-39-s-clothing-quot\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">&quot;Words in Sheep&#39;s Clothing&quot;</h1>\n<p class=\"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-on-surface-variant\">Words that are innocent by themselves but dangerous by how they&#39;re used. Modern worship songs emphasize personal brokenness while minimizing personal sinfulness—framing a narrative that says &quot;I&#39;m in a mess&quot; while refusing to address the cause.</p>\n<h1 id=\"the-problem-with-therapeutic-language\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">The Problem with Therapeutic Language</h1>\n<ol>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Hides culpability</strong> — Brokenness language obscures our own wrongdoing as the cause</li>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Hides gravity of sin</strong> — Sin is rarely described as what it is: grave, destructive, displeasing to God</li>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Compare with hymns</strong> — &quot;Prone to wander, Lord I feel it&quot; (Come Thou Fount) pierces the soul with honest confession</li>\n</ol>\n<h1 id=\"why-this-happens\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">Why This Happens</h1>\n<ol>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Therapeutic age</strong> — Telling someone they&#39;re wrong is seen as unhelpful; counselors avoid spelling out faults</li>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Fear of offending</strong> — Churches fear being called judgmental, legalistic, or unloving</li>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Weak hamartiology</strong> — Many believers don&#39;t understand the depth and willfulness of sin</li>\n</ol>\n<h1 id=\"practical-suggestions\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">Practical Suggestions</h1>\n<ol>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Choose songs with biblical words</strong> — Hymns of old were written after meditation on Scripture</li>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Pair therapeutic songs with biblical songs</strong> — Balance the line-up</li>\n<li><strong class=\"text-on-surface font-semibold\">Remember the goal: God&#39;s glory</strong> — God is glorified when His people are convicted and repent</li>\n</ol>\n<hr class=\"my-12 border-0 border-t border-outline-variant/20\">\n<h1 id=\"concepts\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">Concepts</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">entry.html?slug=worship</a> — The goal of praise is God&#39;s glory, not emotional catharsis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">entry.html?slug=sin</a> — The doctrine of hamartiology; sin as willful rebellion, not mere brokenness</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">entry.html?slug=scripture</a> — God&#39;s Word should fill our worship songs</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">entry.html?slug=church-unity</a> — Guarding God&#39;s people from false teaching</li>\n</ul>\n<hr class=\"my-12 border-0 border-t border-outline-variant/20\">\n<h1 id=\"quotes\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">Quotes</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"pl-8 border-l-2 border-primary-container italic text-xl font-headline text-on-primary-container py-2 my-12\">&quot;What we often repeat is what we teach.&quot;</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"pl-8 border-l-2 border-primary-container italic text-xl font-headline text-on-primary-container py-2 my-12\">&quot;It is like a doctor saying to a cancer patient that the greatest problem he has is the pain he is feeling in his head, not the tumors growing in his head.&quot;</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"pl-8 border-l-2 border-primary-container italic text-xl font-headline text-on-primary-container py-2 my-12\">&quot;God is most glorified when (1) His people are convicted of their sins and they repent and (2) they cry out to God to save them from their sin and misery.&quot;</blockquote>\n<hr class=\"my-12 border-0 border-t border-outline-variant/20\">\n<h1 id=\"related\" class=\"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-headline text-on-surface mt-16 mb-6\">Related</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">entry.html?slug=sugar-coating-the-bible</a> — Parallel warning about redefining biblical words</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"text-primary underline decoration-primary/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-primary transition-all\">entry.html?slug=douglas-wilson</a> — Cited for &quot;when God calls it sin, don&#39;t call it by another name&quot;</li>\n</ul>\n",
